        "question_f4GPDz": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How long does it take to see improvement in redness?",
            "answer": "<h2></h2><ul><li><br/><strong>2–4 weeks:</strong> reduction in irritation and sensitivity<br/></li><li><br/><strong>4–8 weeks:</strong> visible reduction in redness<br/></li><li><br/><strong>8–12 weeks:</strong> improved skin stability and fewer flare-ups<br/></li></ul><p>Redness improves gradually as <strong>inflammation and barrier function are regulated over time</strong>.</p>"
          }
        },
        "q1": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How can an acne protocol help rosacea or redness?",
            "answer": "<p>Rosacea and acne share overlapping pathways:</p><ul><li><br/>Chronic inflammation<br/></li><li><br/>Microbiome imbalance<br/></li><li><br/>Barrier dysfunction<br/></li></ul><p>The Acne Protocol is designed to regulate these systems simultaneously, which is why it can <strong>visibly reduce redness and improve skin stability</strong>, not just breakouts.</p>"
          }
        },
        "q2": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How does this protocol calm redness?",
            "answer": "<p>Through <strong>multi-pathway anti-inflammatory support</strong>:</p><ul><li><br/>Niacinamide reduces inflammation and visible redness<br/></li><li><br/>Barrier-repair ingredients reduce sensitivity<br/></li><li><br/>Microbiome-supportive steps reduce immune activation<br/></li></ul><p>Niacinamide specifically has been shown to <strong>ease inflammation and calm redness in conditions like rosacea</strong>. </p>"
          }
        },
        "q3": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How does the protocol improve a compromised skin barrier?",
            "answer": "<p>Barrier dysfunction is central to rosacea.</p><p>When the barrier is impaired:</p><ul><li><br/>Skin loses water<br/></li><li><br/>Becomes more reactive<br/></li><li><br/>Triggers inflammation<br/></li></ul><p>The protocol supports:</p><ul><li><br/>Ceramide production<br/></li><li><br/>Hydration<br/></li><li><br/>Reduced transepidermal water loss<br/></li></ul><p>Barrier repair has been shown to <strong>improve symptoms and sensitivity in rosacea-prone skin</strong>.</p>"
          }
        },
        "q4": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Can this help with flushing and sensitivity?",
            "answer": "<p>Yes—by improving overall skin stability.</p><p>Redness and flushing are often driven by:</p><ul><li><br/>Barrier weakness<br/></li><li><br/>Inflammation<br/></li><li><br/>Vascular reactivity<br/></li></ul><p>By strengthening the skin and reducing inflammatory signalling, the protocol helps:</p><ul><li><br/>Decrease sensitivity<br/></li><li><br/>Improve tolerance to environmental triggers</li></ul>"
